{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17616134","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17616134"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:00:24+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:00:24+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16383"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16383","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16383"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.79,0,0.13,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9074"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73400"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9074","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9074"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16383"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58867"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4904"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"11340"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21566"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21571"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73400","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/73400"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 62-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with sudden onset of uncontrolled, dance-like movements of her right arm and leg. She has a medical history of hypertension and hypercholesterolaemia, for which she takes amlodipine and atorvastatin. On examination, she appears distressed. Her pulse rate is 88/min, blood pressure 165/95 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.7\u00b0C. She has choreiform movements of her right upper and lower limbs.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following structures is most likely to be affected in this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Putamen","Basal ganglia","Optic chiasm","Posterior limb of internal capsule","Corona radiata"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with acute hemichorea, which may result from a lesion affecting the contralateral basal ganglia. The clinical presentation is consistent with a vascular event affecting these deep grey matter structures.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBasal ganglia\u003C/strong\u003E involvement best explains this patient\u0027s symptoms. The basal ganglia are a group of subcortical nuclei that play a crucial role in motor control. Disruption of these structures, particularly the striatum (putamen and caudate nucleus), can result in various movement disorders including chorea, dystonia, and parkinsonism.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile the \u003Cstrong\u003Eputamen\u003C/strong\u003E is part of the basal ganglia and is commonly involved in movement disorders, the question specifically asks about the broader anatomical structure. The entire basal ganglia network, including connections between its component nuclei, is typically involved in producing choreiform movements.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eoptic chiasm\u003C/strong\u003E is involved in vision and crosses the anterior visual pathways. Lesions here would cause visual field defects rather than movement disorders.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eposterior limb of internal capsule\u003C/strong\u003E contains descending motor fibres and ascending sensory fibres. Lesions here typically cause contralateral hemiparesis and sensory loss rather than choreiform movements.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ecorona radiata\u003C/strong\u003E contains projection fibres running between the cerebral cortex and subcortical structures. While lesions here can cause motor symptoms, they typically manifest as weakness rather than involuntary movements.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The basal ganglia are a group of subcortical nuclei that include the putamen, caudate nucleus, and globus pallidus.","The basal ganglia play a crucial role in motor control, learning, and behaviour.","Lesions of the basal ganglia can result in movement disorders such as chorea, dystonia, and parkinsonism."],"references":["Singh, V. (2024).\u00a0Textbook of Clinical Neuroanatomy-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences.","Michael-Titus, A. T., \u0026 Shortland, P. (2022).\u00a0The Nervous System, E-Book: The Nervous System, E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences.","Lanciego JL, Luquin N, Obeso JA. Functional neuroanatomy of the basal ganglia. Cold Spring Harb Perspect Med. 2012 Dec 1;2(12):a009621. doi: 10.1101/cshperspect.a009621. PMID: 23071379; PMCID: PMC3543080."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58867"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16383"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58867","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/58867"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-23T16:10:30+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-05T07:36:48+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9074"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73400"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeading